27/01/2006
BELGRADE, Serbia-Montenegro -- In an interview with B92 on Thursday (26 January), Serbia-Montenegro Human Rights Minister Rasim Ljajic, who also chairs the national council for co-operation with the UN war crimes tribunal, insisted that authorities do not know where indictee Ratko Mladic is hiding.
He said the Serbian government and Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica are "absolutely" ready to arrest him, if he is located.
Also Thursday, Zagreb announced that the United States has extradited a Serb man to serve a 20-year prison term in Croatia.
Mitar Arambasic was convicted of crimes against humanity by a court in Split in 2000.
He went to the United States the same year as a refugee and was arrested there in September 2002, based on an international arrest warrant.
In other news, a court in Sydney has refused bail to a Serbian man wanted for war crimes in Croatia.
Dragan Vasiljkovic, known as Captain Dragan, is contesting an extradition request.
He was arrested last week.
Croatia has charged the former militia commander, who has dual Serbian and Australian citizenship, with the torture and murder of Croat prisoners during the 1991-1995 conflict.
(Danas, Politika - 27/01/06;
B92, Beta, RTS, AP, AAP - 26/01/06)
